# Background and motivation {background=#00345E}

<!--
## A *different* way of teaching & doing research in political economy

-   Over the course of two years, a series of classroom interventions
    were designed and applied in the Political Economy elective class
    at Facultad de Ciencias Económicas (UNC)
	- main purpose $\longrightarrow$ to enrich learning experience by
      testing key theories, results and concepts in politics and
      political economy [but often *alien* to undergraduate students]

 
## Motivation and literature: voting choice models

-   Pedagogical
    - easier to grasp abstract and theoretical concepts --Condorcet
      winner, single-peaked and single-crossing properties,
      probabilistic two-dimensional voting, etc. 
-   Methodological
    - helps to develop ideas, methods and procedures to understand
      domestic politics and policies
-->	

## The (intended) research agenda

- Research agenda fits along 3 (three) loosely related fields
  1. Voting choice models (PolEcon)
  2. Social identity theory (Social Psychology)
  3. Ideology puzzle/conflicted conservatism (Public Opinion)
- Fueled new directions of research in important political economy
  topics $\longrightarrow$ polarization, democratic backsliding,
  populism and democracy, policy swings, and cognitive processes
  associated with voting

## Motivation and literature: voting choice models

- *Median voter theorem (MVT)* extremely limited as is; increasing
  polarization may render it pretty useless to explain and understand
- Probabilistic voting model (PVM) (aka *swing-voter model*). Voters derive
  utility from:
  - consumption --fiscal policy affects income groups differently
    [policy]	
  - things other than consumption -non-economic policies, candidate
    attributes, group identity, etc [ideology/identity]
- May help to explain why voters go against their
  policy preferences
  - Lindbeck & Weibull (1987), Cukierman (1991), Roemer (1998), Groseclose (2001), Lee & Roemer (2006), 
    Acemoglu et al (2015))
 
## Motivation and literature: voting choice models (cont.)

