# Research agenda #1: Preference ordering and voting choices {background=#00345E}

## Preference and voting

-   Year #1 $\longrightarrow$ single-peak preferences, vote transfer
    and political outcome surveys
	- employed a ranked-choice survey experiment to explore electoral
      preferences among public university students [relatively
      homogeneous course]
-   Year #2 $\longrightarrow$ the probabilistic voting model,
    individual preferences on ideology & policy and the *political
    compass*
	- political compass --ie multidimensional ideology and policy

<!-- 
# *1st Intervention*

First intervention was to employed 

This kind of survey helps analyze how students rank candidates from left to right and create opportunities to test foundational concepts like single peak preferences, vote transfers and agenda power.
-->


## *Single-peaked preferences*: the model

Given $k$ alternatives denoted as $x_1,x_2,...,x_k$, which are ordered linearly, that is, $x_1<x_2<...<x_k$; and individual satisfies this condition if there doesn't exist an alternative $x_s$ such that its neighbouring alternatives ($x_{s-1}$ and $x_{s+1}$) are preferred over $x_s$.

In other words, single-peaked preferences imply that the ordering of alternatives follows a pattern where individual welfare (utility) decreases as alternatives move away from the highest point of preference.

## Individual preferences orderings

Two surveys were run:

-   8th August (before PASO[^1])

-   12th October (before general election)

[^1]: The PASO (Primarias, abiertas, simultaneas y obligatorias) used to have two purposes: (i) Determining which political parties could compete in the general elections (\> 3% of the vote share to qualify), and (ii) selecting each party's official candidate.

Students were asked to rank five candidates from least (1) to most preferred (5) one. In order to produce preference orderings we sourced candidates policy position in a one-dimensional scale from a political compass organized by *La Nación* newspaper.

## First survey: 8th August (PASO)

- Chosen candidates poll were as follows --from top (most left-wing) to bottom (most right-wing):

